The Effect of the 2021 Corporate Tax Decrease on DRC’s GDP

Mateus Berutto Figueiredo

2025-03-21

Introduction

In 2020, the Democratic Republic of the Congo had the fourth highest corporate tax rate in the world, behind only Comoros, Suriname, and Puerto Rico. In an attempt to increase investment, improve business competitiveness, and stimulate economic growth, the Congolese government decided to lower the corporate tax rate from 35% to 30%. This reports seeks to analyze the impact of this decision on the Congolese economy and to simulate an alternative world where the tax policy had not changed. To do this, I adopt a synthetic control method (SCM) analysis, building a “synthetic” version of the DRC to analyze the causal impact of the decision and simulate an alternative scenatio.

Method

Synthetic Control Method (SCM) is used to estimate the causal impact of an intervention when a traditional control group is unavailable. SCM constructs a synthetic counter-factual by weighting a combination of untreated units (donor countries) to match the pre-treatment characteristics of the treated unit (DRC) as closely as possible. In the context of evaluating the impact of the 2021 corporate tax cut in the DRC from 35% to 30% on GDP, SCM enables us to estimate what DRC’s GDP per capita would have been had the tax cut not occurred by comparing actual GDP trends to those of the synthetic control. By implementing SCM, we can quantify the effect of the tax policy on GDP and simulate alternative tax scenarios.

Reading tax data

To carry out this analysis, I downloaded data on corporate tax rates across the world from the Tax Foundation, a research think tank that collects and publishes tax policy data from across 251 countries and territories. More specifically, I used data from their 2024 Corporate Tax Rates Around the World report, which can be found here and can be downloaded by clicking the “DOWNLOAD HISTORICAL DATA” button.

# Read in the data
tax_data <- read.csv("rates_final.csv") 

# Removes the column named "X"
tax_data <- tax_data %>%
  select(-X)  

# Remove "X" from year column names
colnames(tax_data) <- gsub("^X", "", colnames(tax_data))

After retrieving the data, I will not clean it to only include African countries between 2013 and 2023. I only picked African countries for my donor pool to ensure comparability by selecting economies with similar regional, structural, and developmental characteristics to the DRC, reducing bias in the synthetic control estimation. My data collection will start in 2023 because that was the last time the Congolese government updated their corporate tax rate prior to the 2021 change. By setting 2013 as my lower bound, I ensure that my analysis is focusing on only on the impact of one change in tax policy on the DRC’s GDP. Despite having corporate tax data up until 2024, I picked 2023 as my upper bound because data from the World Bank World Development Indicators, which will be used to create the synthetic treatment group, have not yet been published for 2024.

# Cleaning data
tax_data <- tax_data %>%
  filter(continent == "AF") %>% # Select only African countries
  select(iso_2, `2013`:`2023`) %>% # Between 2013 and 2023
  na.omit() # Remove rows with NA values

Lastly, I selected only countries that did not change their corporate tax rate between 2013 and 2023 and stored them in the variable countries. This ensures that the synthetic control is built from economies that were not influenced by similar tax policy changes, isolating the effect of the DRC's 2021 corporate tax reduction.

# Finding all countries that did not change their corporate tax rate between 2013 and 2023 to form the donor pool
countries <- tax_data %>%
  group_by(across(`2013`:`2023`)) %>%  
  summarize(countries = paste(unique(iso_2), collapse = ", "), count = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%  
  filter(count > 1) %>%  
  pull(countries) %>%
  paste(collapse = ", ")

countries <- unlist(strsplit(countries, ", "))

Collecting data from the World Bank API

I now use the World Bank World Development Indicators API to retrieve socio-economic data for DR Congo (i.e., the treated unit) and for the donor countries selected previously.

Data on countries’ GDP per capita will be used as the as the outcome variable in this analysis. I chose to use GDP per capita as the dependent variable instead of nominal GDP because it provides a more accurate and comparable measure of economic performance, especially given the large size of the DRC, and allows for a clearer estimation of the counter-factual scenario by accounting for population size. Moreover, GDP per capita enables the calculation of a counter-factual scenario for the DRC's total GDP without the intervention, thus providing a basis for simulation.

I selected additional variables such as unemployment, exports as a proportion of GDP, and investment to improve the accuracy of the synthetic control by capturing key economic factors that influence GDP per capita.

# List of countries to remove (due to missing data)
countries_to_remove <- c("Djibouti", "Eritrea", "Liberia", "Malawi", "Nigeria")

# Remove rows where the 'country' column matches any of the specified countries
df <- df[!df$country %in% countries_to_remove, ]

Building synthetic DRC

I know build the synthetic DRC for my analysis. First, I create a numerical mapping of each country, a necessary step to use the dataprep() function.

# Assign unique numeric identifiers to each country
df <- df %>%
  mutate(unit_id = as.numeric(as.factor(country)))

# Create a mapping of country names to numeric IDs
country_mapping <- df %>% select(unit_id, country) %>% distinct()

# Define the treated country
treated_country <- "Congo, Dem. Rep."

# Get numeric ID of the treated country (DRC)
treatment_id <- country_mapping$unit_id[country_mapping$country == treated_country]

# Get numeric IDs of donor countries
donor_countries <- country_mapping$unit_id[!country_mapping$unit_id %in% treatment_id]

Next, I implement a randomized search approach to identify the optimal set of predictor variables for the Synthetic Control Method (SCM) analysis. Rather than exhaustively testing every possible predictor combination—an approach that would be computationally intensive—I randomly select subsets of predictor variables and evaluate their performance over 100 iterations. The effectiveness of each subset is assessed by minimizing the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE), which measures how well the synthetic control replicates the pre-treatment GDP per capita trends of the DRC. The predictor combination that results in the lowest RMSE is chosen as the best model for constructing the synthetic DRC.

# Define the full list of possible predictors
all_predictors <- c("Investment_GDP", "Exports_GDP", "Unemployment", "Life_Expectancy", "Infant_Mortality_Rate", "Access_to_Electricity", "Inflation",
"Oil_rents", "Rule_of_Law", "Control_of_Corruption", "Political_Stability", "Government_Effectiveness")

set.seed(89)  # Ensure reproducibility
iterations <- 50  # Number of search iterations
best_rmse <- Inf  # Track best RMSE found
best_predictors <- NULL  # Store best predictor set
results <- list()

for (i in 1:iterations) {
  
  # Randomly select a subset of predictors (ensuring at least 4 predictors)
  num_vars <- sample(4:length(all_predictors), 1)  
  
  predictors <- sample(all_predictors, num_vars, replace = FALSE) 

  # Run dataprep with selected predictors
  dataprep_out <- dataprep(
    foo = df,
    predictors = predictors,
    dependent = "GDP_per_capita",
    unit.variable = "unit_id",
    time.variable = "year",
    treatment.identifier = treatment_id,
    controls.identifier = donor_countries,
    time.predictors.prior = 2013:2020,
    time.optimize.ssr = 2013:2020,
    time.plot = 2013:2023
  )
  
  # Run Synthetic Control Model
  synth_out <- synth(dataprep_out)
  
  # Extract actual and synthetic values for pre-treatment period (2013-2019)
  actual_values <- dataprep_out$Y1plot[1:7]  # Actual GDP per capita
  synthetic_values <- dataprep_out$Y0plot %*% synth_out$solution.w  # Synthetic GDP per capita
  
  # Compute RMSE
  rmse <- sqrt(mean((actual_values - synthetic_values)^2))

  # Store results
  results[[paste(predictors, collapse = ", ")]] <- rmse
  
  # Update best RMSE and predictor combination if lower RMSE is found
  if (rmse < best_rmse) {
    best_rmse <- rmse
    best_predictors <- predictors
  }
}

Implementing Best Model

Now, I run the SCM analysis using the best predictors found in the randomized search.

# Preparing data for SCM analysis using the best predictors
dataprep_out <- dataprep(
  foo = df,  
  predictors = best_predictors,  # Best predictors
  dependent = "GDP_per_capita",  # Outcome variable
  unit.variable = "unit_id",  # Numeric country identifier
  time.variable = "year",  # Time variable
  treatment.identifier = treatment_id,  # DRC country ID
  controls.identifier = donor_countries,  # Donor country IDs
  time.predictors.prior = 2013:2020,  # Pre-treatment period for matching
  time.optimize.ssr = 2013:2020,  # Period to optimize Synthetic Control
  time.plot = 2013:2023  # Full time period (pre and post-treatment)
)

# Running SCM analysis with the best predictors
synth_out <- synth(dataprep_out)

The results of the SCM are best understood by seeing a visualization of the synthetic and treated DRC. In the pre-treatment period between 2013 and 2020, both lines are close closer with minor deviations in 2013, 2015, and 2020, although the difference between the two never exceed $16, less than 4% of Congo’s total GDP per capita. However, from 2021 to 2023, the gap between the two lines widens, suggesting the five percentage point decrease in the corporate tax rate did lead to an increase in GDP per capita.

# Extract years

Another way of visualizing the treatment effect is through a gaps plot, which displays the difference between the actual GDP per capita of the treated unit (DRC) and its synthetic counterpart over time. This allows for a clearer interpretation of the effect of the corporate tax cut by highlighting how the observed GDP per capita deviates from the counterfactual scenario where the tax policy change did not occur. A positive gap after the treatment year suggests the tax cut had a positive impact on GDP per capita.

# Gaps plot
gaps.plot(synth_out, dataprep_out, tr.intake = 2021, Ylab = "GDP per Capita Difference", Xlab = "Year")

From the gaps plot, I extract the difference between the synthetic and treated unit and present it in the table below, again showing that the difference increases significantly post-treatment, indicating that the tax cuts increased GDP per capita and simulating the GDP per capita has Congo not adopted this policy.

At first, it might seem counter-intuitive that only a few countries have non-zero weights. However, this is normal in SCM analyses because the optimization process selects a minimal weighted combination of donors that best replicate the pre-treatment characteristics of the treated unit.

Moreover, in addition to having the lowest RMSE, which measures how well the synthetic control replicates the pre-treatment GDP per capita trends of the DRC, Loss W is also very low, indicating donor weights were well optimized to construct the synthetic DRC.

synth_tables <- synth.tab(dataprep.res = dataprep_out, synth.res = synth_out)

## [1,] 0.02208479 103.2422

Limitations

Firstly, the analysis could be improved with higher computer power and more complete data. With higher computational power, this study could be reevaluated and use grid search - as opposed to randomized search - to find the optimal parameter combination. Moreover, there was a lot of missing data for some countries in the donor pool, which meant that not all predictor variables could be considered for all years and that some countries (Djibouti, Eritrea, Liberia, Malawi, and Nigeria) has to be dropped. This could potentially be used to increase certainty in our predictions.

Moreover, one key assumption of the SCM is that there is no interference between units, meaning that the tax policy change in the DRC should not indirectly affect the economies of the countries in the donor pool. A primary concern is that the DRC's tax policy change may have influenced regional investment flows, particularly in neighboring countries with economic ties to the DRC. If businesses redirected investment from donor pool countries to the DRC due to the lower corporate tax rate, this could have depressed economic growth in donor countries, making the synthetic control less accurate. However, this potential violation may attenuate rather than exaggerate the estimated effect of the corporate tax cut and thus it does not pose a serious threat to the broad findings of this analysis.

Placebo test

# Initialize a list to store placebo results
placebo_results <- list()

# Iterate over each donor country and apply the Synthetic Control Method
for (placebo_unit in donor_countries) {
  
  # Print progress
  cat("\nRunning placebo for:", country_mapping$country[country_mapping$unit_id == placebo_unit], "\n")

  # Prepare the data with placebo treatment
  dataprep_out_placebo <- dataprep(
    foo = df,  # Use long-format data
    predictors = best_predictors,  # Use the same best predictors
    dependent = "GDP_per_capita",  # Outcome variable
    unit.variable = "unit_id",  # Numeric country identifier
    time.variable = "year",  # Time variable
    treatment.identifier = placebo_unit,  # Assign placebo treatment
    controls.identifier = donor_countries[donor_countries != placebo_unit],  # Exclude placebo-treated unit
    time.predictors.prior = 2013:2020,  # Pre-treatment period for matching
    time.optimize.ssr = 2013:2020,  # Optimize synthetic control over pre-treatment years
    time.plot = 2013:2023  # Full time period (pre and post-treatment)
  )

  # Run synthetic control method
  synth_out_placebo <- synth(dataprep_out_placebo)
  
  # Compute the treatment effect for the placebo country
  placebo_effect <- dataprep_out_placebo$Y1plot - (dataprep_out_placebo$Y0plot %*% synth_out_placebo$solution.w)
  
  # Store results
  placebo_results[[country_mapping$country[country_mapping$unit_id == placebo_unit]]] <- placebo_effect
}
# Convert placebo results into a dataframe for plotting
placebo_df <- as.data.frame(do.call(cbind, placebo_results))

# Add a Year column
placebo_df$Year <- 2013:2023  

# Ensure column names match formatting expectations
colnames(placebo_df) <- c(names(placebo_results), "Year")

# Reshape the placebo dataframe to long format for ggplot
placebo_long <- placebo_df %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -Year, names_to = "Country", values_to = "Effect")

# Ensure Country column is a character
placebo_long$Country <- as.character(placebo_long$Country)

# Ensure treatment effect dataframe has the correct structure
treatment_effect_df <- treatment_effect_df %>%
  mutate(Year = 2013:2023,  # Add Year column
         Country = "DRC")   # Add Country column

# Rename the first column to "Effect" for consistency
colnames(treatment_effect_df)[1] <- "Effect"

# Ensure Country column is character in both dataframes
treatment_effect_df$Country <- as.character(treatment_effect_df$Country)

# Combine real and placebo effects into a single dataframe
all_effects <- bind_rows(placebo_long, treatment_effect_df)

# Define pre-treatment and post-treatment periods
pre_treatment_years <- 2013:2020
post_treatment_years <- 2021:2023

# Compute MSPE for each country (including DRC)
mspe_df <- all_effects %>%
  group_by(Country) %>%
  summarise(
    Pre_MSPE = mean((Effect[Year %in% pre_treatment_years])^2, na.rm = TRUE),
    Post_MSPE = mean((Effect[Year %in% post_treatment_years])^2, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  mutate(Ratio_MSPE = Post_MSPE / Pre_MSPE)  # Compute ratio

# Create the plot
ggplot(mspe_df, aes(x = reorder(Country, Ratio_MSPE), y = Ratio_MSPE)) +
  geom_col(fill = "gray") +  # Use geom_col() instead of geom_bar()
  geom_col(data = mspe_df %>% filter(Country == "DRC"), aes(x = Country, y = Ratio_MSPE), fill = "red") +  
  coord_flip() +  # Flip for better readability
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Ratio of Post/Pre-MSPE for Placebo and Treated Unit",
    x = "Country",
    y = "Post-MSPE / Pre-MSPE"
  ) +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 14))
